There is however plenty of briskness and life in the Eunuchus (what can be more entertaining than the parasite's account of his method of gaining a livelihood ῗὶ); in the closing scene of the Phormio and in the third act of the Adelphoe, where Demea’s sententious remarks and righteous maxims are echoed and pai-odied by the slave Syrus3 while the dry hu- mour of the scene in the Phormio with the foolish advisers is of no ordinary quality³⁴. If tragedy and comedy are to be defined by the denouement, then Terence is undoubtedly a comedian3 but his comedies are mainly of the sentimental kind: they belong to what the F rench call ‘genre serieux' and ‘comedie larmoyante’: there is a want of mirth (especially in the Hecyra and Heautontimorumenos) and the pathos is at times almost painful: witness particularly the touching opening of the Andria.

We turn next to the handling of the plot. Here Plots. Terence exhibits considerable skill, except that his trick of making the heroine almost invariably turn out to be an Athenian citizeness becomes a little worn by frequent use. He is hampered too in point of simplicity by the custom of contaminatio already alluded to.
